What "antibodies" and "immunity" should we get from an epidemic?

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On January 29, the fifth day of the Lunar New Year, a patient who had been diagnosed with new coronary pneumonia was transferred to a hospital on Jiefang Avenue in Hankou, Wuhan. Photo / Yangtze daily, Kim sze-ryu

Epidemic "RASHOMON" : patients, doctors and decision-makers

Chinese philanthropist journalist / Wen Rujun, Wu Keyan

Published in the February 2020 issue of Chinese philanthropist

It is not often in the history of the republic that a city changes the pace of an entire nation.

This is a protracted "war epidemic" . From the New Year's Day to the Spring Festival, until the spring flowering season, people still do not see the sign of the closing Gong.

The wind begins at the end of the duckweed. Looking back, what happened to the city in 2019 and 2020, when the old and the new came together? Doctors, patients and decision-makers are supposed to be the basic relationship of benign interaction in the public health system. How did it evolve into an "impossible triangle" ? Painful reflection, we should get from the epidemic in what "antibody" and "immunity" ?

Chapter 1: Patients on the brink of death

The dead, the living, the waiting, in this "war epidemic" , they can not control their own destiny.

The dead

Wang Zhuangzhuang, 67, is an ordinary retired worker from a family with a genetic disorder of the heart. From suspected cold hospitalization to "severe pneumonia" death, only 14 days. He was the first patient to die in the outbreak, but was not a confirmed case and did not appear on the government's death list, which said "severe pneumonia" .

On December 23,2019, Wang Zhuangzhuang was treated in Wuhan Union Medical College Cancer Hospital, Union Medical College Hospital and Jinyintan Hospital, but he died in Jinyintan hospital on January 7,2020. After the patient passed away, the hospital asked the family to donate the body for a medical autopsy. The family refused and the body was cremated on the same day. Doctors told the family that Wang was the first person to die from the outbreak.

How exactly did Wang Zhuangzhuang get infected? His family still doesn't know. On December 20,2019, he felt unwell and hiccupped for three days straight. Wang Zhuangzhuang's lover is in the advanced stage of pancreatic cancer, has been in Wuhan Xiehe Tumor Hospital treatment, every half a month to the hospital to take medicine. Therefore, Wang Zhuangzhuang also came to the hospital for an examination.

At that time, "new crown pneumonia" was a completely unfamiliar concept to ordinary citizens, Wang Zhuangzhuang just suspected that he had a cold. In this hospital, the doctor took his pulse and told him that his heart rate was irregular. "We do have inherited heart disease in our family, " Wang Lan, Wang's sister, told China philanthropist, but she did not share the information with doctors.

After further auscultation, the doctor suggested that Wang Zhuangzhuang take a CT scan of the lung. The results showed lung infection. The doctor suggested hospitalization, Wang Lan in the same day went through the hospital procedures. "The hospital just started treating Emphysema with traditional Chinese medicine, " said Ms. Wang, who often communicates with her brother on the phone, feeling his condition worsen each time she calls, because she lives far from the hospital.

"I feel more and more uncomfortable after being hospitalized, " Wang told Wang Lan on Dec. 29. On the phone, his sister could hear him gasping for air. On Dec. 30, Wang took an hour by subway to the cancer hospital. It was noon. She told the nurse on duty that she wanted to see the attending doctor about her brother's condition. The nurse told her that the doctor would be on duty at 2:30. See the illness aggravated brother, Wang Lan insisted to see the attending doctor, some emotional excitement. The nurse telephoned the doctor.

Then, Wang Lan saw the doctor, asked his brother got what disease, why so long not good but aggravated? The two sides of the language conflict, the doctor dissatisfaction Wang Lan on its "treatment program" questioned. "You'll have to ask professor X  , " said the doctor. "He wrote the prescription. ". Professor x appeared did not explain too much, just told the family, if the hospital does not trust, discharged today. After signing the discharge papers, Wang asked his daughter, Wang Qian, to register as a general physician at Wuhan Union Hospital. As it was already evening, they did not leave the oncology hospital.

On the same day, a report allegedly issued by the Wuhan Municipal Health and Health Commission, "on doing a good job of pneumonia of unknown causes of emergency notice. ". According to the notice, patients with pneumonia of unknown cause have been found in some medical institutions in Wuhan, and the relevant medical institutions are required to provide proper medical treatment. This is the first sign of "new coronary pneumonia" .

The next day, the Wuhan Municipal Health and Health Commission issued its first announcement: Some medical institutions have recently found that more than one pneumonia case has been linked to the south China seafood market, and 27 cases have been found, of which 7 cases are in serious condition, the remaining cases are stable and controllable, with 2 cases improving and to be discharged in the near future. It was the first time that the virus was recognized as a "new pneumonia" -- a "viral pneumonia" , with no obvious human-to-human transmission and no medical staff infection.

Wang Zhuang Zhuang accompanied by his family came to the Union Hospital, at this time he needs someone to help him walk, and walk two steps on the big gasp. "We can't treat you in general internal medicine. You must go to the emergency room now, " the doctor told them after seeing him. The emergency physician wants a CT of the lungs. When the results came back, the family showed the doctor a CT scan taken on Jan. 23. Only a week later, the doctor couldn't believe it was the same man: His lungs had turned completely white.

Doctors Suspect AIDS, Lung Morphology and AIDS patients are almost terminal is the same. Wang Zhuang Zhuang Zhuang was also arranged to do a stream, syphilis, AIDS testing, the results were negative. Afterward, the doctor gave the family to give the critically ill notice, and told the family: If the treatment is likely to lose both money and money, treatment or give up? After the answer is positive, the Concorde Hospital will be the expert of smoking department to consult.

On 1 January 2020, Wang Zhuangzhuang was transferred to the respiratory ICU ward. The doctor told the family, Wang Zhuangzhuang got the disease only know is a viral infection, but can not find what the virus is, there is no way to treat, can only use the existing antibiotics.

"We also expressed our understanding. After all, we had a disease we had never seen before, and no one could do anything about it. " Whether it was daughter Wang Qian or sister Wang Lan, they all had one wish, that is, to make their loved ones better, even if it's only 1% . After running out of both methods and drugs, doctors advised the family to transfer the patient to the hospital on Jan. 3. In the transfer, Wang Lan and Wang Qian after consultation agreed that only listen to the doctor's advice, there is no other way.

At this point, Wang Zhuang depends on breathing life, but conscious. Wang Lan asked him: "Plug in the machine feel better? " , was the answer is "all of a sudden feel from Hell on heaven. Unexpectedly, this turned out to be Wang Zhuangzhuang's last words to his family.

Survivors

Mr. Wu was the first critically ill patient to be cured from the Wuhan outbreak, and in late December 2019, he was infected with COVID-19 and briefly hospitalized at intensive-care unit, narrowly missing his death. He spent two nights staring at the ceiling in intensive-care unit, afraid he'd fall asleep and never wake up. After 14 days in isolation, he had no symptoms other than a dry cough.

Mr. Wu, a native of Huanggang, Hubei Province, runs a poultry business in a local vegetable market, and although he has never been to the south China Seafood Market, he has frequent contacts with merchants who buy from it. At the end of December last year, he found that he had a "cold" , no appetite at all, had not eaten for several days, then had a high fever. Because his father had just died, Mr. Wu had no time to go to the doctor. It took him a week to get to the hospital, and the scans showed a shadow on his right lung. He had three days of anti-inflammatory fluids and a CT scan of his lungs, both of which were cloudy.

"I'm usually in good health. I rarely go to the hospital. The cold usually goes away in three or two days, but this time it's not normal, " Mr. Wu told the Chinese philanthropist. The cold dragged a week, infusion three days did not get better, double lung problems, which let Mr. Wu suddenly nervous. Three years ago, a relative died of kidney failure after catching a cold that took so long that he developed pneumonia.

After consulting with his family, he was taken directly to Wuhan by ambulance for treatment on Jan. 5. By this time, the Wuhan Union Hospital and Tongji hospitals were overcrowded and had no beds. Came to Wuhan University Zhongnan Hospital, also has no bed. One thing led to another, and it took two days.

On January 7, Mr. Wu had a high fever of 39.3 degrees and developed symptoms of dyspnea. Doctors at Zhongnan Hospital immediately arranged a temporary bed for him. Subsequent CT scans showed that both lungs were white. After urgent discussion and comprehensive evaluation of Mr. Wu's indexes, he was treated with ECMO. He became the first patient in Wuhan to be treated with the technique.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Peng Yong (right) , director of the intensive-care unit, holds a handheld ultrasound device to assist Huang Xiaobo (center) , director of the Center for Critical Care Medicine of the Sichuan Provincial People's Hospital, in using ECMO technology to rescue patients in the ICU ward of the Wuhan Red Cross Hospital on February 9,2010. Photo / Hubei Daily, Ke Hao

"ECMO technology is not 'killing' the virus, more precisely, it is an auxiliary treatment, " said Xia Jian, deputy director of the emergency center of Zhongnan Hospital at Wuhan University. Patients with COVID-19 infection have lung damage, placing an artificial membrane lung outside the body to replace the lungs helps patients get through the toughest times. When the patient's lungs can assume the body's functions, the artificial heart-lung machine can be removed.

At this time, Mr. Wu was conscious, anesthesia, cardiopulmonary resuscitation and oxygen machine, do ekg... a series of actions he remembered, but the body is too weak to even lift the hand. Feeling cold all over, he motioned the doctor to cover himself with an extra blanket. He felt so sleepy that he clenched his fists and kept straining his feet to keep from falling asleep. So he stared at the ceiling for two days and nights without sleeping. "after falling asleep, one's willpower will be weak, and I'm afraid I'll never wake up again, " Mr. Wu said.

At the intensive-care unit, he had daily fluids in his veins and kept drawing blood for biological markers, taking his temperature, his blood pressure and his heart rate. After five days of intensive treatment, Mr. Wu's condition began to improve, apparently feeling a little bit better. Even the doctor was moved by his willpower and gave him a thumbs-up every ward round.

"It was faith that kept me going, " Mr. Wu said, from the time he needed a doctor to feed him to the time he picked up his chopsticks. Five days later, a CT scan showed a marked improvement in his lungs, he was then transferred to a general ward. On January 28, Mr. Wu was officially discharged from the hospital, becoming the first critically ill patient to recover from the outbreak.

When he was discharged from the hospital, Mr. Wu asked the doctor if there would be any sequelae in his body. The doctor told him, "according to the situation on the CT scan, your lung has recovered 90 percent, basically the same as normal people, there will be no sequelae. "

The waiting man

After days of waiting, Mr. Min couldn't get a bed.

A 44 year old truck driver, he had volunteered to deliver supplies to government departments at the 2008 Sichuan Earthquake. Since January 22, Mr. Min has been suffering from repeated high fever. He was found to have lung lesions at the East West Lake People's Hospital in Wuhan. He is a "highly suspected" patient of new crown pneumonia. On February 2, he developed severe respiratory distress and was unable to walk or eat.

Initial diagnosis is a suspected case, can only at home self-isolation, to the late critical stage and can not be admitted to treatment. In Wuhan, Mr Min is not alone in his inability to find a bed. FACEBOOK and twitter are flooded with requests for help in need of a hospital bed. More let Mr. Min family anxiety is, two children also appeared similar to the new coronary pneumonia symptoms, the fate of an old and young do not know what to do.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Wang Ke and the 72-year-old man ran four hospitals in a row, beds have been full, but he did not give up, and finally the hospital admitted the elderly Concorde Hospital. Photo / Changjiang Daily, Jin Zhenqiang

On the morning of Jan. 30, there was a long line at the Wuhan Union Hospital's fever clinic, where workers in protective clothing directed patients and kept order. Mr Wang, who has had a fever for four days, sat slumped on the curb next to the hospital, where he had been diagnosed with a new coronavirus infection, but there were no beds.

"The daily number of suspected and confirmed cases is growing too fast and there is nothing we can do, " a head of the hospital's publicity department told China Philanthropist.

On January 28, Jiao Yahui, deputy director of the medical and Health Administration Bureau of the National Health Commission, said at a press conference that Wuhan will adopt the "10 + 10" model, in which people from 10 major hospitals will contribute their personnel, skills and strength, requisitioning of 10 small and medium-sized hospital venues, beds and medical personnel, as designated hospitals admitted suspected cases and confirmed cases.

Still, the number of cases is rising. Another objective reason for the shortage of beds is that many hospitals lack isolation wards that meet the requirements. Ordinary wards can not prevent and control viruses, and isolation wards require high requirements, except for setting up isolation wards in different districts, indoor equipment, and even air-conditioning system are strict requirements, many hospitals can not fully do.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Medics prepare beds at a converted shelter hospital at the Wuhan International Convention and Exhibition Center on Feb. 5. Photograph by Wen Rujun, China philanthropist

Two temporary hospitals with more than 2,500 beds were built at Mount Vulcan and Mount Thor, and a shelter hospital with more than 10,000 beds was built. February 5, the new pneumonia prevention and control headquarters meeting in Hubei Province stressed that to speed up the resolution of bed tension, to ensure that "should be collected, should be treated. ".

On the same day, Zhang Zuofeng, an international public health expert and deputy dean of the Public Health at UCLA, suggested in an interview with Chinese Philanthropist magazine that more attention should be paid to Hubei, and the patients in Henan and Hunan, which are adjacent to Hubei Province, are not only diagnosed as suspected patients, but more importantly, they are diagnosed as fever clinics and people with fever, cough and other symptoms, turning suspected patients into confirmed patients. Only by diagnosing the potential patient can the nation hope to see an inflection point.

The "inflection point" came a week later. According to the National Health Commission, between 0000 and 2400 hours on February 12, there were 14,840 new cases of coronary pneumonia in Hubei Province (13,436 in Wuhan) and 1,310 deaths in the whole province (including 1,036 in Wuhan) .

Amid the incessant cries for help, how many people waited in despair and even lost their lives before the arrival of the carpet search? It's impossible to keep track of them all.

Chapter two: the doctor in the crevice

From early December 2019 found cases, early January 2020 appeared a certain scale patient infection, Wuhan local release said "no obvious human-to-human transmission" , everyone believed. As a result, more than 10 million Wuhan residents, plus nearly 5 million migrant population in a city without any protection at will flow.

"It's impossible, in the common sense of a doctor, that the disease can not be transmitted from person to person, " he said. first-line doctors, as witnesses and whistle-blowers, ignored their professional judgment and intuitive feelings until the outbreak.

I know it in my heart

On the morning of December 26,2019, an elderly couple from a nearby community were admitted to the Hubei Provincial Hospital of traditional Chinese and Western medicine. They walked to the hospital for treatment because of fever and cough. Zhang Jixian, director of the Department of aspiration and Critical Care Medicine of the hospital, looked at the CT scan and found that, both of their lungs showed completely different symptoms from the other viral pneumonia.

Clinical Experience Rich Zhang Jixian first thought of infectious disease, she let the old couple call their son to do tests, no symptoms, but CT a picture, the same performance in the lungs. On this day, also came a south China Seafood Market Merchant, the same fever, cough, the same lung performance. Hubei Integrated Traditional Chinese and Western Medicine Hospital is one of the two closest level-iii hospitals to the south China Seafood Market. The distance between them is less than two kilometers in a straight line.

"generally speaking, when a family comes to see a doctor, there will only be one patient, and not three people will get the same disease at the same time, unless it is an infectious disease, " Zhang told the Changjiang daily, she tested the patients for Influenza A, influenza B, chlamydia, Mycoplasma and other flu-related tests, all negative, thus ruling out the flu. It is worth mentioning that when fighting SARS in 2003, Zhang Jixian, then 37, was a member of the Jianghan District expert group, whose daily task was to go down to various hospitals to screen for suspected cases.

Zhang Jixian first realized the seriousness of the problem. On December 27, she reported the situation of the four people to the business director Xia Wenguang, the hospital sentiment office and the medical department. The hospital immediately reported the situation to the Kong Hon CDC. December 28,29 two days, the outpatient clinic has been admitted to the same 3 from the south China Seafood Market patients, similar patients reached 7.

"This is a disease we have never seen before. There are four patients from the south China Seafood Market, which must be a problem. " Zhang Jixian judged that the symptoms of the seven patients were consistent with the lung performance, but there was a difference in severity. Zhang Jixian keenly aware of the situation, and immediately to the hospital for a report, and suggested that the hospital to hold multi-sectoral consultation.

At 1:00 p.m. on December 29, the deputy director in charge, Xia Wenguang, convened a meeting of 10 experts from the departments of respiratory, cardiovascular and ICU to discuss each of the seven cases, special imaging, systemic symptoms, laboratory examination of muscle enzymes and liver enzymes have changed, experts agree that this situation is indeed abnormal, it should be given high priority.

After inquiring that there were two similar patients who had been to Tongji Hospital, Xiehe Hospital for treatment and left the address of the South China Seafood Market, Xia Wenguang immediately decided to report to the higher authorities. After receiving the report, the provincial and Municipal Health and Health Commission's Disease Control Office directed the Wuhan Center for Disease Control, Jinyintan Hospital and the Kong Hon District Center for Disease Control to hospitals to begin an epidemiological investigation, the Changjiang Daily reported.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A group of community doctors walk across Changdi Street in Hankou, Wuhan, on Jan. 29, the fifth day of the Lunar New Year. Photo / Yangtze daily, Kim sze-ryu

"At this point, many departments have realized that the problem is quite serious, and doctors know it best, " a doctor involved in treating patients told the Chinese philanthropist. December 29, several doctors involved in the "SARS" treatment of seven patients, we dare not to "SARS" up, but we "know in my heart.

"This is serious. "

Wang Min (not her real name) is a mother of two. As the head nurse of the infection department of a third-class hospital in Wuhan, she can't remember how long she hasn't been home with her children. Since December, when there was a high incidence of influenza a, patients have been pouring into hospitals. At most, Wang Min's department treated more than 20 children with swine flu in one night.

After midnight still working overtime, for her has become a regular meal during that time, always feel there are "endless patients. ". Sometimes she took a nap in the on-call room and began to receive patients early the next morning. It was so hard that some colleagues in the department even quit their jobs.

"The whole hospital is just running over capacity, " Wang told China philanthropist, adding that the number of patients reached a peak on Dec. 29, when 82 children were admitted to Wang's department. Around 11:00 noon that day, the hospital leadership suddenly informed the medical staff to hold a temporary meeting. At the meeting, the leadership did not say too much information, but only informed that "the afternoon to start to receive unexplained pneumonia patients, " the need to prepare the ward.

The head of the department, Li Dan (not his real name) , demurred: "This would pose a serious threat to more than 80 children. " But in the end, the decision to admit patients with pneumonia of unknown origin was carried out. "The treatment cycle for H1N1 is usually three to five days, and I try to get the children out of the hospital if they can, and protect those who can't, " Li Dan told China philanthropist on Dec. 29, more than 80 children with a flu basically all discharged from the hospital.

Together with Wang and other colleagues, Li Dan set up an isolation ward for seven patients with "pneumonia of unknown origin" who had been transferred from other hospitals. By the end of the day, they had 10 more patients with the same symptoms.

Li Dan had been in the business for decades, as the hospital's first suspected SARS patient, in 2003, known as SARS, was handled by Li Dan. It was also with years of experience and intuition that she made the decision to establish an isolation ward. According to Li Dan recalled, on December 29 received more than a dozen patients with pneumonia of unknown cause, whose clinical manifestations were mainly fever, a few patients with dyspnea, chest radiographs showing bilateral lung infiltrates.

According to the regulations, each to the flu season, the hospital will be careful to deal with fever patients. In the same period last year, the average number of fever clinic visits in Wuhan was about 3,000 per day, according to official figures. That number climbed as high as 15,000 after the outbreak this year. At its peak, 40,000 people a day attended fever clinics in Hubei Province, the provincial health and Health Commission said on Jan. 29.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
At 9 a.m. on Jan. 30, Wang Ke, a 34-year-old doctor at Wuhan Emergency Center, and his team were tasked with transporting a resident of Evergreen Garden suspected of COVID-19 pneumonia to a hospital. Photo / Changjiang Daily, Jin Zhenqiang

But even on the night of December 29, Li Dan was "shocked" by a dozen or so cases of pneumonia of unknown origin. On Monday, Dec. 30, more and more patients came to the hospital with the same symptoms, some even showing symptoms of dyspnea. More than forty beds in Li Dan's ward filled quickly that day.

In the days that followed, as more patients continued to arrive, Li Dan sensed that things were getting serious. "because there was no awareness of the disease and the patient was emotionally unstable, there was already a voice saying 'sars' was coming back and people were filled with fear, " Li Dan recalled.

She began to tell the staff to protect themselves, but also to calm the entire ward patients psychological. "round-the-clock" has become the norm for doctors and nurses, who are afraid to drink water at work "because they don't know when to get up when they sit down" . To make matters worse, despite all the experience and precautions, some of the nurses in Li Dan's ward were infected.

"from man to man. "

With years of professional experience in infectious diseases, Li Dan was struck by what would later be called the "COVID-19" case. In her department, medical staff stepped up protection while collecting Bronchoalveolar lavage fluid from the seven patients and sending it to the Wuhan Institute of Virology of the Chinese Academy of Sciences for testing.

The Wuhan Virus Institute works closely with Li Dan's hospital. On April 23,2019, the two institutions signed a joint research agreement, under which the two sides will cooperate in the fields of Hand, foot and mouth disease, AIDS, influenza and upper respiratory tract infection diseases, tuberculosis, etc. , to further promote the integration of basic and translational medical research and clinical, and comprehensively enhance the scientific research capabilities of both sides.

In the ward, the level of protection has been raised to the highest level. "It wasn't just a general shield, it was a tertiary shield, " Li Dan said. According to the relevant regulations, medical protection is divided into first, second and third levels. Second-level protection requires relevant medical personnel to wear more than 12 layers of cotton gauze mask, work clothes, isolation clothes, shoe covers, gloves and work caps when entering isolation observation rooms and special wards, hand washing and disinfection should be carried out immediately after each contact with the patient. The three-level protection is applicable to the medical personnel who perform sputum suction, tracheotomy and tracheal intubation for the patients. On the basis of the two-level protection, a full-type suction protector should be added. "level three protection" is the highest level of protection, almost all day was wrapped in protective clothing, like a person stuffy in a thick plastic bag, "through the N95 mask, do not speak, already began to breathe heavily

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Medical workers treat a suspected case of COVID-19 pneumonia at the emergency center of Zhongnan Hospital of Wuhan University on Jan. 28. Photographer Chinese philanthropist, Anyuan District

"If it was just a normal infectious disease, how could we have been able to isolate patients and go to tertiary protection without knowing it? " Li Dan asked reporters as he recalled the experience to China philanthropist. Vigilance begins, she said, and for many doctors with experience in infectious diseases, the severity of the problem can be seen at a glance in a patient's CT scans. On the same day, a specialist exchange group, found suspected SARS news spread like wildfire, news is not groundless.

"The patient tested to be SARS, what to do? " On December 30, a second-generation sequencing colleague Li Dan knew sent wechat. Li Dan called the hospital authorities the same day to report the situation. No one answered her phone and she left a message on Wechat. "You're talking nonsense again, you're talking about the patients at Tongji Hospital, " Li Dan was later scolded by the leader. "I'm not talking about Tongji University's patients, I'm talking about our patients, " Li Dan said, explaining that if only Tongji had contracted the strange disease, the problem might not be that big, but other hospitals had similar cases, this is definitely a sign of contagion.

Soon, Wuhan Tongji Hospital colleagues due to "rumors" were interviewed and punished. Li Dan asked his best friend, who wasn't speaking, in a cryptic way, adding to the sense that things weren't easy. Hospital leaders let Li Dan to colleagues to "suspected SARS" patients CT, see the CT film, Li Dan is more firm on the "infectious" judgment. In retrospect, Li Dan was particularly grateful for his decision to discharge more than 80 children, or else the consequences would have been unimaginable.

Over the next few days, the hospital was overwhelmed. On December 30th, with more than 40 beds full in Li Dan's department, the hospital began to break up other wards for pneumonia patients.

"By the end of December, we had determined that the infectious virus was related to the south China seafood market because most of their patients knew each other. Some of the patients even said, where my relatives are in the hospital where the dying Ah. They're either a family or they play Mahjong together,"Li Dan told the Chinese philanthropist, some of the first patients were either directly related to the south China seafood market or lived near the market and were cluster cases.

"By the end of December, the signs of human-to-human transmission were so obvious that anyone with a little common sense could tell, " Li Dan said.

Chapter 3: The slow decision maker

Experts believe that the local government has the responsibility of not declaring the "epidemic" or "epidemic area" , the information has been made public, and through early warning to alert the public to raise awareness of prevention.

But that didn't happen, and it went in the opposite direction, even weirdly.

Seal Up

On December 30,2019, the pneumonia epidemic first came into public view after people such as Zhang Jixian of Hubei Province Integrated Traditional Chinese and Western Medicine Hospital reported the epidemic layer by layer. On the same day, the Wuhan Health Commission issued an "urgent notice on doing a good job in the treatment of pneumonia of unknown causes, " which stressed that "no individual shall release information on treatment without authorization from any unit. ".

A well-intentioned reminder from a young man in a wechat group has opened a gap in the "sealed" epidemic. At 17:43 that evening, Li Wenliang, a 33-year-old ophthalmologist at Wuhan Central Hospital, announced in a group of about 150 students that "seven cases of SARS have been confirmed in the south China seafood market. " He reminded fellow clinicians to "let family members and loved ones take precautions. ". Li Wenliang also became the first to the outside world to issue a protective early warning.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Mourners placed a photo of Li in front of flowers in the courtyard where he worked. Photograph by Wen Rujun, China philanthropist

A group friend posted a screenshot of his conversation online, without omitting the most crucial information: His name and occupation. This made it easy for the screenshot viewer to find Li Wenliang, who was interviewed by the Hospital Supervision Department the next day and asked to write a reflection on the misinformation.

On December 31, the Wuhan Municipal Health and Health Commission issued its first report on the city's epidemic of pneumonia. The circular confirmed that some medical institutions had recently found that many pneumonia cases were related to south China Seafood City, and 27 cases had been found so far, of which 7 cases were serious, no significant human-to-human transmission was found, and no infection among medical staff was found. The circular also said that after testing and analysis of the cases of viral pneumonia, "the disease can be controlled. ". At this time, the cause of this unknown but "preventable and controllable" disease, did not arouse public attention.

But for some of the medical staff who already know, they clearly can not understand and accept the above statement. However, in addition to the private communication with colleagues this matter, they also dare not "publicity. ".

On the first day of 2020, Wuhan's Public Security Bureau released a message saying that some medical institutions in Wuhan had received many cases of pneumonia, but some netizens posted and reposted false information on the Internet without verification. The Public Security Bureau subpoenaed eight people and dealt with them in accordance with the law.

On the same day, the Wuhan Municipal Government also closed the south China Seafood Wholesale Market. The South China Seafood Market, at the heart of the storm, is a large local complex that houses more than 1,000 merchants and is within 800 meters of the crowded Hankou Railway Station.

On January 2,2019, the complete genome of COVID-19 was sequenced by Wuhan Virus Institute of the Chinese Academy of Sciences. On the same day, the National Health Commission set up a team led by Ma Xiaowei to deal with the epidemic.

As of 0800 hours on January 3,44 patients had been diagnosed with viral pneumonia for unknown reasons, of which 11 were critically ill, Wuhan's health commission said in a second notice on January 3. On the same morning, Li Wenliang in the district police station signed a "warning letter, " because "on the Internet to publish false statements, " the police admonished him.

"It's so cold! If the authorities had made the situation clear at the beginning, 50 to 60 percent of the people would have taken precautions, " Lin Yu, a doctor at the Wuhan Union Hospital, told China Newsweek, when the outbreak began, Wuhan's strategy was to "cool it" .

His hospital informed him that it would not allow him to talk about his illness privately on public platforms or give interviews to the media without the authorization of the unit. Not only the clinical system, including the hospital administration and the CDC, but also the information control there is more serious, the whole thing is off limits.

At that time, doctors can only do is repeatedly told patients: "Masks, masks, must buy masks, wear masks. ". They even half-jokingly told everyone, "do not go to the south China Seafood Market to buy things, where things are not fresh. "

Seal off the city

In a third circular issued on January 5, the Wuhan Municipal Health Commission concluded that "no clear evidence of human-to-human transmission has been found, and no infection among medical personnel has been found. "

On Jan. 6, the Yangtze daily, the official newspaper of the Communist Party of China's Wuhan Municipal Party Committee, published a front page report titled "When Wuhan Enters the two sessions. ". Until the closing of the Wuhan two sessions on the 11th, Wuhan Health and Health Commission did not issue an outbreak of pneumonia of unknown causes.

It was not until January 14 that the Wuhan Health Commission, in its seventh circular, changed "no visible human-to-human transmission" to "no exclusion of limited human-to-human transmission" . It was now the 20th day of the 12th Lunar Month, and many citizens had not felt nervous or alarmed by the ambiguous announcements. Most of them were still happy to leave the old and welcome the new. More than 40,000 families attended the 10,000 family banquet held in Wuhan's Baibu Pavilion Community on Jan. 18, local media reported.

On January 20, at a press conference on the prevention and control of the "COVID-19 pneumonia epidemic" , national Health Commission senior Expert Group leader Zhong Nanshan confirmed that Wuhan Pneumonia "person-to-person" , and there are medical staff infection. At this point, the situation has been "uncontrollable" reversal.

As early as 10 days ago, the 2020 National Spring Festival transportation has officially started, the number of people leaving Wuhan is many times than usual, the epidemic has also multiplied in silence. Nearly five million people left the city around the Lunar New Year holiday, according to Wuhan Mayor Zhou Xianwang, who later told a news conference.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Residents wear masks as they make phone calls in an alley at the Shengsheng Bridge in Wuhan on Feb. 3,2010. In the distance is the city's iconic Yellow Crane Tower, which has been known as the "Best Under Heaven" since ancient times. Photo / Hubei Daily, Ke Hao

According to statistics, from January 10 to 22, the largest outflow of people from Wuhan was to the surrounding areas of Wuhan, with Huanggang and Xiaogan being the two cities with the largest concentration of people. Among the cities from other provinces, between January 10 and 15, changsha, Beijing, Chongqing, Shanghai and other relatively advanced; January 15-22, Wuhan outflow of population to Sichuan Chengdu, Henan Xinyang, Zhumadian and Chongqing City is very obvious.

The arrival of the annual Spring Festival travel peak, hundreds of millions of people or home or travel, to the "controllable" to the "human-to-human" epidemic prevention and control of the great challenge, the only way is to take extreme measures. On January 23, public transport in Wuhan was suspended, leaving the Han corridor temporarily closed, and the city was officially declared closed.

January 27th, "As a local government, I had to obtain information and be authorized to disclose it, which was not understood at the time, " Zhou Xianwang, the mayor of Wuhan, said in an interview with CCTV. He added: "It wasn't until later, especially on January 20, when the State Council held an executive meeting to confirm the disease as a category B infectious disease and to manage it as a category a infectious disease, and to require the territories to take responsibility, that we took the initiative and took some tough measures in many areas, not half-time, but a hard time. "

Two days later, on January 29, zeng Guang, a senior expert from the National Health Commission and Chief Scientist of Epidemiology at the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention, told the Global Times whether the response to the Wuhan outbreak was "slow. ". He said Wuhan's response to the epidemic was somewhat slow, mainly a matter of scientific understanding, but did not rule out some hesitation in decision-making and self-confidence.

Mechanism

Professor, a professor at Peking University Law School, told China philanthropist that the release of the outbreak is a very special kind of voluntary disclosure of government information, the subject of disclosure is indeed the State Council and the State Health Administration Department. From the limits of authority, the Wuhan Municipal Government can not issue an epidemic without authorization, but the local government has the responsibility to make public the information it has obtained without declaring an "epidemic" or an "epidemic area. " And through the early warning way lets the populace be on guard, raises the guard the consciousness.

Combing through the history of the epidemic in the past two months, no expression related to "early warning" can be found either in the blank period in December last year or in the official bulletin of Wuhan Municipal Health and Health Commission, which has been issued irregularly since January 5 this year.

In an interview with Chinese philanthropist, public health, an international public health expert and deputy dean of the Ucla School of Medicine, said that in the early days of the outbreak, the slow pace of prevention and control of government departments, measures did not keep up, there is a delay in the process, is one of the main reasons for the national outbreak.

Zhang also believes that the response to the epidemic has fully exposed many flaws in China's public health system, including the lack of public health personnel, many measures did not catch up in time, some government departments of public health preventive medicine, and so on. Its negative effects are also obvious, such as in the initial phase of the epidemic did not fully use public health epidemiology, preventive medicine experts to guide the epidemic prevention, which is a great lack.

He further analysis that due to the government and administrative departments usually pay insufficient attention to preventive medicine, public health, insufficient investment, the national and Provincial Centers for Disease Control and control lost many excellent epidemiologist experts. "The role of public health and preventive medicine is to prevent disease from occurring or to control infectious diseases at the earliest stages of an outbreak. However, the CDC and public health units are not profitable, resulting in low incomes and lack of respect in society. Some areas have abolished the CDC or merged it into hospitals. At the same time, students in preventive medicine and public health don't get enough attention, and many students don't use them after graduation, leaving the CDC without a successor."

Zhang urged the state to attach great importance to public health and disease control systems, and to strengthen investment in improving disease control systems and public health from the central to the local level through the control process of the outbreak. "We hope that this new outbreak of pneumonia will serve as a wake-up call for leaders to start paying attention to the cause of public safety and build a strong disease prevention and control team that can be called upon to win the battle. "

Yu Xiaodong, a senior media person living in Singapore, told the Chinese philanthropist that Singapore is the country with the most severe infection of the new coronavirus outside China, the measures of the Chinese government in the prevention and control of new coronaviruses have certain enlightenment and reference significance to China.

"The Singapore government has long been regarded internationally as a model of technocracy. "technocracy is defined as the decision-making process by highly skilled technocrats. It is characterized by minimizing political and ideological considerations in decision-making, emphasizing the dominance of science, technology and expertise. It is different from the decision-making mechanism in Western democracies, where elected representatives are the core, and from the traditional authoritarian system where power is concentrated, " Yu said.

According to his observations, the government's response since the new crown outbreak began in Singapore has been largely technocratic. "The first confirmed case of the new coronavirus in Singapore occurred on January 23, when he was a tourist from Wuhan who flew from Guangzhou to Singapore. On the same day that Wuhan announced the closure of the city, the Singapore government immediately set up temperature checks and other measures at the airport to isolate Chinese tourists with abnormal body temperatures. By Jan. 27, Singapore had confirmed seven cases, all of them tourists from Wuhan, and the government had issued a level three yellow alert. On February 3, Singapore had its first local case, and the government raised the alert level to yellow, and then to orange after a cluster of cases on February 7."

Singapore's epidemic preparedness plan, known as Dorscon, was developed by the Ministry of Health in 2005, after the SARS virus, and was first launched in 2009 during the H1N1 flu epidemic, with the last update in 2014, according to the agency. Under the plan, a crisis management system in the event of an outbreak would be provided with strategic and political guidance by a joint meeting of ministers chaired by the Minister of the Interior, the head of the Crisis Response Implementation team is also the permanent secretary, who is the highest-ranking official in the Ministry of the Interior.

"The plan describes in great detail how to deal with the situation in terms of defensive measures, cross-departmental coordination of the government, border control, public communication, procurement of emergency supplies and so on. It deals with the Organization of early treatment, the adoption of measures to reduce the spread of the virus and the impact on the health system, and provides for the protection of health personnel, the provision of basic social services and the continuity of commerce. The plan also provides guidelines for quarantine, treatment, contact quarantine, visits and even disposal of bodies in the event of an outbreak."

Yu Xiaodong believes that under the respective systems and countermeasures of China and Singapore, the new outbreak can finally be brought under control. For China, respecting the due position of science in decision-making should be the greatest common denominator of the unity of Chinese society at present.

Wang Zhuangzhuang, Wang Lan, Wang Qian, Wang Min, and Li Dan are all pseudonyms to protect the privacy of the interviewees
